2:Tc37,[{"@context":"https://schema.org","@type":"Article","headline":"Best Pressure Washers for Florida Driveways and Lanais — Top 5 Picks | TB Relo","description":"Best pressure washers for Florida homes. Electric vs gas, PSI guide for driveways and lanais, top 5 picks, and how often to pressure wash in Florida's humidity.","url":"https://tbrelo.com/blog/best-pressure-washers-florida/","author":{"@type":"Person","name":"Barrett Henry","jobTitle":"REALTOR® & Broker Associate","url":"https://nowtb.com","worksFor":{"@type":"Organization","name":"REMAX Collective"}},"publisher":{"@type":"Organization","name":"TB Relo","url":"https://tbrelo.com"},"datePublished":"2026-04-13","dateModified":"2026-04-13","image":{"@type":"ImageObject","url":"https://tbrelo.com/images/blog/best-pressure-washers-florida.jpg"}},{"@context":"https://schema.org","@type":"FAQPage","mainEntity":[{"@type":"Question","name":"Is it worth hiring a pressure washing service in Florida?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"For the driveway and house exterior, hiring a pro ($150–$300 for a standard driveway, $200–$400 for house wash) makes sense if you hate doing it yourself. For the lanai and pool deck, those are quick jobs better handled with your own electric washer. Many Florida homeowners own a pressure washer for routine work and hire a pro for the big annual house wash and roof soft-wash."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"Can I pressure wash my Florida screen enclosure?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Yes, but carefully. Use the lowest pressure setting (under 1,500 PSI) with a wide nozzle (40-degree white tip) and keep the spray at a 45-degree angle to the screen — never perpendicular. Too much pressure or too close a distance tears the screen mesh. Rinse from top to bottom."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"Does pressure washing remove the stain from pavers?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"If your pavers are stained (sealed with a colored sealant), aggressive pressure washing can strip the sealant. Use moderate pressure (1,500–2,000 PSI) and reapply paver sealer after washing. Unsealed pavers can handle higher pressure without issue, but you'll need to re-sand the polymeric sand joints after washing."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"Why does my driveway get black so fast after pressure washing?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Because you didn't seal it. Clean concrete in Florida's humidity is a blank canvas for mold spores. Apply a concrete sealer with mold inhibitor within 24 hours of washing (let the concrete dry completely first). This extends the clean look from 2–3 months to 6–9 months."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"What time of year is best for pressure washing in Florida?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Any time — Florida mold doesn't take a season off. However, spring (March–April) is ideal for a thorough wash before the wet season starts. The dryer winter air lets surfaces dry faster after cleaning, which helps sealers cure properly. Avoid washing during active rainstorms (obviously) or immediately before a storm is forecast."}}]}]5:T4288,<h2>Why Pressure Washing Is a Florida Essential, Not a Luxury</h2>
<p>In most of the country, pressure washing your driveway is something you do every few years when it starts looking dingy. In Florida, it's a regular maintenance task — and skipping it creates real problems.</p>
<p>Florida's combination of heat, humidity, rain, and shade creates a perfect breeding ground for mold, mildew, algae, and lichen on every exterior hard surface. Your concrete driveway, lanai pavers, pool deck, sidewalks, house exterior, fence, and even your roof will develop black/green growth that's not just ugly — it's slippery and can cause falls, especially on pool decks.</p>
<p>Here's what Florida humidity does to surfaces if you don't pressure wash:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Driveways:</strong> Black mold streaks appear within 3–4 months on north-facing or shaded concrete. Within a year, the driveway looks like it hasn't been cleaned in a decade.</li>
<li><strong>Lanai pavers and pool decks:</strong> Green algae growth makes the surface dangerously slick when wet. One slip on a slimy pool deck and you're dealing with a broken bone.</li>
<li><strong>House exterior (stucco, vinyl, block):</strong> Mold grows on the north side and under eaves where rain splash keeps the surface damp. Dark streaks run down from gutters and window frames.</li>
<li><strong>Fences:</strong> Vinyl fences turn green. Wood fences turn black. Both happen within 6 months without maintenance.</li>
<li><strong>Screen enclosures:</strong> Pool cage screens collect mildew, reducing visibility and making the whole lanai look neglected.</li>
</ul>
<p>A pressure washer handles all of this. It's one tool that pays for itself in the first use when you consider that hiring a professional to pressure wash your driveway runs $150–$300, and you'll need it done 2–4 times per year in Florida.</p>
<h2>Electric vs. Gas — Which One for Florida?</h2>
<h3>Electric Pressure Washers</h3>
<p><strong>Best for:</strong> Lanais, screen enclosures, outdoor furniture, cars, sidewalks, small driveways, light mold removal.</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>PSI range:</strong> 1,300–2,300 PSI (most residential electric models)</li>
<li><strong>Pros:</strong> Lighter, quieter, no fumes (safe for enclosed lanai use), no gas/oil maintenance, start instantly</li>
<li><strong>Cons:</strong> Less powerful, limited by cord length and outlet proximity, can't handle heavy-duty jobs as efficiently</li>
<li><strong>Best pick:</strong> See recommendations below</li>
</ul>
<h3>Gas Pressure Washers</h3>
<p><strong>Best for:</strong> Large driveways, heavy mold/algae buildup, pool decks, house siding, fences, anything requiring 2,500+ PSI.</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>PSI range:</strong> 2,500–4,000+ PSI</li>
<li><strong>Pros:</strong> More powerful, portable (no cord), handles large jobs faster</li>
<li><strong>Cons:</strong> Heavier, louder, requires gas and oil, pull-start (harder to start in Florida humidity), exhaust fumes (never use in enclosed spaces)</li>
<li><strong>Best pick:</strong> See recommendations below</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>My recommendation:</strong> Own both. A $150 electric for routine lanai and light cleaning (every month), and a $300+ gas unit for quarterly driveway and heavy-duty work. If you can only buy one, get a gas model in the 2,700–3,200 PSI range — it handles everything but requires more setup for small jobs.</p>
<h2>PSI Guide — What Pressure for What Surface</h2>
<p>Using too much pressure damages surfaces. Using too little wastes your time. Here's the Florida-specific guide:</p>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Surface</th>
<th>Recommended PSI</th>
<th>Nozzle Tip</th>
<th>Notes</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>Concrete driveway</td>
<td>2,500–3,000</td>
<td>15° or 25° (yellow/green)</td>
<td>Use a surface cleaner attachment for even results</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Pavers (sealed)</td>
<td>1,500–2,000</td>
<td>25° or 40° (green/white)</td>
<td>High PSI blows out joint sand — go gentle</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Pavers (unsealed)</td>
<td>2,000–2,500</td>
<td>25° (green)</td>
<td>Re-sand joints and seal after washing</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Pool deck (concrete)</td>
<td>2,000–2,500</td>
<td>25° (green)</td>
<td>Rinse toward drains, keep chemicals out of pool</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Pool screen enclosure</td>
<td>1,000–1,500</td>
<td>40° (white) or low-pressure</td>
<td>Too much pressure tears screens</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Stucco house exterior</td>
<td>1,500–2,000</td>
<td>25° or 40° (green/white)</td>
<td>Stucco chips at high PSI — keep distance</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Vinyl siding</td>
<td>1,300–1,500</td>
<td>25° or 40° (green/white)</td>
<td>Water can get behind siding at high PSI</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Wood fence</td>
<td>1,500–2,000</td>
<td>25° (green)</td>
<td>Let wood dry 48 hours before sealing</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Vinyl fence</td>
<td>1,500–2,000</td>
<td>25° (green)</td>
<td>Easy — vinyl cleans up fast</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Outdoor furniture</td>
<td>1,000–1,500</td>
<td>40° (white)</td>
<td>Keep distance on wicker and cushions</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Roof (soft wash only)</td>
<td>Low pressure + chemical</td>
<td>Low-pressure nozzle</td>
<td>Never high-pressure a roof — damages shingles/tile</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<h2>Top 5 Pressure Washers for Florida</h2>
<h3>1. Sun Joe SPX3000 Electric — Best Budget Electric</h3>
<p><a href="https://www.amazon.com/s?k=Sun+Joe+SPX3000+electric+pressure+washer&#x26;tag=tbrelo-20">Sun Joe SPX3000 Electric Pressure Washer</a></p>
<p>The most popular electric pressure washer on Amazon for good reason. At 2,030 PSI and 1.76 GPM, it handles lanai cleaning, outdoor furniture, cars, sidewalks, and light driveway maintenance. Two detergent tanks let you pre-mix cleaning solutions for mold treatment.</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>PSI:</strong> 2,030</li>
<li><strong>GPM:</strong> 1.76</li>
<li><strong>Motor:</strong> Electric (13-amp)</li>
<li><strong>Weight:</strong> 31 lbs</li>
<li><strong>Price:</strong> $150–$190</li>
<li><strong>Florida verdict:</strong> Perfect for monthly lanai and screen enclosure maintenance. Light enough to carry around the house, quiet enough to use without bothering neighbors, and powerful enough for most routine Florida cleaning. Won't handle a heavily stained concrete driveway as efficiently as a gas model.</li>
</ul>
<h3>2. Ryobi 2,300 PSI Electric — Best Mid-Range Electric</h3>
<p><a href="https://www.amazon.com/s?k=Ryobi+2300+PSI+brushless+electric+pressure+washer&#x26;tag=tbrelo-20">Ryobi 2300 PSI Electric Pressure Washer</a></p>
<p>Steps up to 2,300 PSI with a brushless motor that lasts longer in Florida's humidity. The turbo nozzle provides a concentrated blast for stubborn mold spots without switching to a gas machine. Ryobi accessories are widely available at Home Depot — easy to find replacement nozzles and hoses locally.</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>PSI:</strong> 2,300</li>
<li><strong>GPM:</strong> 1.2</li>
<li><strong>Motor:</strong> Electric (brushless)</li>
<li><strong>Weight:</strong> 36 lbs</li>
<li><strong>Price:</strong> $230–$280</li>
<li><strong>Florida verdict:</strong> The sweet spot between the budget Sun Joe and a gas model. Handles pavers, sidewalks, and moderately dirty driveways without the hassle of gas. The brushless motor won't burn out as fast in Florida's heat.</li>
</ul>
<h3>3. Simpson MegaShot 3,200 PSI Gas — Best Value Gas</h3>
<p><a href="https://www.amazon.com/s?k=Simpson+MegaShot+3200+PSI+gas+pressure+washer&#x26;tag=tbrelo-20">Simpson MegaShot 3200 PSI Gas Pressure Washer</a></p>
<p>Honda GC190 engine (the most reliable small engine you can buy), 3,200 PSI that eats through concrete mold and algae, and a price that's competitive with lesser brands using off-brand engines. Simpson is a commercial-grade brand used by professional pressure washing services.</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>PSI:</strong> 3,200</li>
<li><strong>GPM:</strong> 2.5</li>
<li><strong>Engine:</strong> Honda GC190</li>
<li><strong>Weight:</strong> 62 lbs</li>
<li><strong>Price:</strong> $350–$420</li>
<li><strong>Florida verdict:</strong> This is the one. If you're buying one gas pressure washer for your Florida home, the Simpson with the Honda engine is the best combination of power, reliability, and value. The Honda engine starts reliably even after sitting in a humid garage for months — which is more than you can say for generic engines.</li>
</ul>
<h3>4. Generac SpeedWash 3,200 PSI Gas — Best for Large Properties</h3>
<p><a href="https://www.amazon.com/s?k=Generac+SpeedWash+3200+PSI+gas+pressure+washer&#x26;tag=tbrelo-20">Generac SpeedWash 3200 PSI Pressure Washer</a></p>
<p>Generac's pressure washer line includes a power broom and a turbo nozzle in the box — accessories that usually cost $50–$100 extra. The power broom is particularly useful for large Florida driveways because it covers a wider cleaning path and prevents the "striping" you get with a standard nozzle.</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>PSI:</strong> 3,200</li>
<li><strong>GPM:</strong> 2.7</li>
<li><strong>Engine:</strong> Generac OHV (196cc)</li>
<li><strong>Weight:</strong> 68 lbs</li>
<li><strong>Included accessories:</strong> Power broom, turbo nozzle, soap blaster, standard nozzle</li>
<li><strong>Price:</strong> $400–$500</li>
<li><strong>Florida verdict:</strong> If you have a long driveway, large pool deck, or a two-story home with extensive stucco, the included power broom and higher GPM make this worth the premium over the Simpson. The Generac engine is solid but not quite Honda-reliable.</li>
</ul>
<h3>5. Greenworks Pro 3,000 PSI Electric — Best Powerful Electric</h3>
<p><a href="https://www.amazon.com/s?k=Greenworks+Pro+3000+PSI+electric+pressure+washer&#x26;tag=tbrelo-20">Greenworks Pro 3000 PSI Electric Pressure Washer</a></p>
<p>An electric that matches gas-level PSI without the gas hassle. The brushless motor and PWMA certification mean this is a true 3,000 PSI (some brands exaggerate), and the electric operation means you can use it in the lanai without choking on exhaust.</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>PSI:</strong> 3,000</li>
<li><strong>GPM:</strong> 2.0</li>
<li><strong>Motor:</strong> Electric brushless</li>
<li><strong>Weight:</strong> 45 lbs</li>
<li><strong>Price:</strong> $350–$430</li>
<li><strong>Florida verdict:</strong> If you refuse to deal with gas engines (understandable — maintaining gas equipment in Florida humidity is annoying), this is the most powerful electric option that handles concrete driveways competently. Not quite as fast as a gas model with the same PSI due to lower GPM, but it gets the job done.</li>
</ul>
<h2>Essential Accessories</h2>
<ul>
<li><a href="https://www.amazon.com/s?k=pressure+washer+surface+cleaner+15+inch&#x26;tag=tbrelo-20">Surface Cleaner Attachment (15-inch)</a> — Transforms driveway cleaning. Instead of a narrow stream that leaves stripes, the surface cleaner covers 15 inches in even, circular passes. Cuts driveway cleaning time in half and produces dramatically better results. This is not optional for driveway work.</li>
<li><a href="https://www.amazon.com/s?k=pressure+washer+detergent+mold+mildew+outdoor&#x26;tag=tbrelo-20">Pressure Washer Detergent (Mold/Mildew)</a> — Pre-treat heavy mold with detergent before pressure washing. Apply at low pressure, let sit 5–10 minutes, then blast. Makes a massive difference on severely stained surfaces.</li>
<li><a href="https://www.amazon.com/s?k=pressure+washer+turbo+nozzle+rotating&#x26;tag=tbrelo-20">Turbo Nozzle</a> — Concentrates the spray into a spinning pinpoint for stubborn spots. Use on concrete and pavers; don't use on anything delicate.</li>
<li><a href="https://www.amazon.com/s?k=pressure+washer+extension+wand+24+inch&#x26;tag=tbrelo-20">Extension Wand (24-inch)</a> — Reaches second-story soffits and high fascia without a ladder. Critical for cleaning the upper walls and eaves of Florida two-story homes.</li>
</ul>
<h2>How Often to Pressure Wash in Florida</h2>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Surface</th>
<th>Frequency</th>
<th>Why</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>Driveway</td>
<td>Every 3–4 months</td>
<td>Mold and algae return fast in shade and moisture</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Lanai / pool deck</td>
<td>Every 2–3 months</td>
<td>Algae = slip hazard; high use area</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>House exterior</td>
<td>Every 6–12 months</td>
<td>North and east sides need it most (less sun, more mold)</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Fence</td>
<td>Every 6 months</td>
<td>Green algae covers vinyl fences quickly</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Screen enclosure</td>
<td>Every 6–12 months</td>
<td>Mildew reduces light and looks terrible</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Roof</td>
<td>Annually (soft wash only)</td>
<td>Black streaks from gloeocapsa magma algae</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p>Compare this to northern states where you might pressure wash once every 2–3 years. Florida's climate demands more frequent maintenance.</p>
<h2>Pro Tips for Florida Pressure Washing</h2>
<ul>
<li><strong>Wash in the morning</strong> — surfaces are coolest, detergent doesn't evaporate before it works, and you beat the afternoon thunderstorms.</li>
<li><strong>Pre-treat mold with bleach solution</strong> (1 part bleach to 10 parts water) for heavily stained concrete. Let it sit 10 minutes before pressure washing. Wear old clothes.</li>
<li><strong>Rinse toward drains, not toward your pool</strong> — pool chemicals react badly with bleach and detergent runoff.</li>
<li><strong>Seal concrete and pavers after washing</strong> with a <a href="https://www.amazon.com/s?k=concrete+driveway+sealer+acrylic&#x26;tag=tbrelo-20">concrete sealer</a> to slow mold regrowth. Sealed surfaces stay cleaner 2–3 times longer.</li>
<li><strong>Never pressure wash your roof at high pressure</strong> — it strips the protective granules off shingles and cracks tile. Roofs need "soft washing" (low pressure + chemical treatment). Consider hiring a professional for this ($200–$400).</li>
<li><strong>Store your pressure washer in the garage</strong> with fuel stabilizer (gas models) and run antifreeze through the pump if storing long-term. Florida humidity corrodes pump internals if left with standing water inside.</li>
</ul>
<h2>What to Skip</h2>
<ul>
<li><strong>Pressure washers under 1,500 PSI</strong> — not worth the money. They take forever on Florida mold and leave you frustrated. Spend a little more for real results.</li>
<li><strong>Turbo nozzle on delicate surfaces</strong> — the turbo nozzle will etch concrete (permanent circular marks), destroy soft stucco, and blow holes in screen enclosures. Use the appropriate nozzle for each surface.</li>
<li><strong>Renting instead of buying</strong> — rental pressure washers cost $50–$75/day. You'll need to pressure wash 4–8 times per year in Florida. After two rentals, you've paid for the Sun Joe. Buy your own.</li>
</ul>
<h2>FAQ</h2>
<h3>Is it worth hiring a pressure washing service in Florida?</h3>
<p>For the driveway and house exterior, hiring a pro ($150–$300 for a standard driveway, $200–$400 for house wash) makes sense if you hate doing it yourself. For the lanai and pool deck, those are quick jobs better handled with your own electric washer. Many Florida homeowners own a pressure washer for routine work and hire a pro for the big annual house wash and roof soft-wash.</p>
<h3>Can I pressure wash my Florida screen enclosure?</h3>
<p>Yes, but carefully. Use the lowest pressure setting (under 1,500 PSI) with a wide nozzle (40-degree white tip) and keep the spray at a 45-degree angle to the screen — never perpendicular. Too much pressure or too close a distance tears the screen mesh. Rinse from top to bottom.</p>
<h3>Does pressure washing remove the stain from pavers?</h3>
<p>If your pavers are stained (sealed with a colored sealant), aggressive pressure washing can strip the sealant. Use moderate pressure (1,500–2,000 PSI) and reapply <a href="https://www.amazon.com/s?k=paver+sealer+wet+look&#x26;tag=tbrelo-20">paver sealer</a> after washing. Unsealed pavers can handle higher pressure without issue, but you'll need to re-sand the polymeric sand joints after washing.</p>
<h3>Why does my driveway get black so fast after pressure washing?</h3>
<p>Because you didn't seal it. Clean concrete in Florida's humidity is a blank canvas for mold spores. Apply a <a href="https://www.amazon.com/s?k=concrete+sealer+mold+mildew+inhibitor&#x26;tag=tbrelo-20">concrete sealer with mold inhibitor</a> within 24 hours of washing (let the concrete dry completely first). This extends the clean look from 2–3 months to 6–9 months.</p>
<h3>What time of year is best for pressure washing in Florida?</h3>
<p>Any time — Florida mold doesn't take a season off. However, spring (March–April) is ideal for a thorough wash before the wet season starts. The dryer winter air lets surfaces dry faster after cleaning, which helps sealers cure properly. Avoid washing during active rainstorms (obviously) or immediately before a storm is forecast.</p>
